The Eclectic principle, that had influenced in a greater or less degree the teaching of every one of the ancient masters, gave a far more impulsive movement to the phi- losophy of Alexandria. The first Macedonian colonists‚ as barbarians, owed no fealty to the schools of Greece. Eastern adventurers, linking their fortunes with those of the rising city, introduced modes of thought and theories that had from time immemorial formed the traditions of the East.
